description:
&lt;p&gt;An excellent opportunity has arisen for a suitably qualified practitioner to undertake ADHD assessments, reviews and titrations for adults and follow up appointments to patients diagnosed with ADHD across the geographical area of the Trust whilst collaboratively working within the MDT.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applicants will possess excellent communication and interpersonal skills, with a proven track record. You will work in a highly supported environment as an active member of the multidisciplinary team. The team is a diagnostic and treatment service and an awareness of this level of service provision would be deemed a benefit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There will be support to increase and develop knowledge and understanding of the challenges faced by adults with potential ADHD in adulthood. There will an expectation to be able to demonstrate competency within this specialised area of ADHD assessment and treatment pathways. The applicant will be required to empathetic to the needs of people post diagnosis of ADHD and have good understanding of the services that are available to ‘signpost’ to within the NTW area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You must have a strong commitment to the delivery of high quality, safe, patient care.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Information from a newly appointed community nurse practitioner to give an insight in the role.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As a band 6 Community Nurse Practitioner, within the Adult ADHD Service, I regularly carry out assessments. This includes gaining background history and using clinical knowledge to understand whether the person may be suffering from co-morbid mental health problems. I also contact service user’s family in order to gain developmental history. I also attend formulation meetings to share my findings and discuss diagnosis with the wider team. I am also regularly involved in triage of referrals and am able to give my opinion on whether the referral is sufficient and details symptoms of ADHD, in order to offer an assessment. I have regular supervision with my manager and clinical lead. The things that I like about the role are that the team are very approachable and always happy to help, despite current restrictions. I like that I am trusted to work with my own diary, in order to complete tasks. I feel a valued member of the team and always know there is someone there, if need be. I enjoy getting to find out about people&#39;s lives and to then move them on through the treatment pathway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Name: Paul Wilson&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Job title: Team Manager&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Email address: paul.wilson@cntw.nhs.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Telephone number: 0191 287 6250&lt;/p&gt;
